## Definitions\
\
# Design System Definitions\
\
Ubiquitous language is a cornerstone of communicating effectively in an organization, so let's all get on the same page with a glossary of common terms used in design systems, component libraries, and modern product development.  \
\
## What is a Design System?\
\
A design system is simply a set of building blocks and standards that help make the experience of designing, developing, and, importantly, *using* different application more efficient and consistent.\
\
Think of it as a structured framework that guides teams through the complex process of creating digital products that are visually consistent, accessible, and usable without every team having to reinvent the wheel every time they start a new project.\
\
Most people, when they hear "design system", immediately think of *component library*, such as Material UI or Vuetify or something like Bootstrap, but component libraries, and code in general, are just one part of a design system, and, in some cases, not even the most important part.\
\
Coefficient is a design system that includes components, code, design tools, patterns & recipes, accessibility guidance, and other tools all backed by research and industry standards and driven by the unique needs and diverse technology stacks found at Oak Ridge National Laboratory.\
\
## Frequently-used Terms\
\
Below are some common terms that you will find throughout this documentation and in other material about Coefficient.\
\
### Accessibility (a11y)\
\
Practices that ensure digital products can be used by people of all abilities, including those with disabilities.  See our <Link to="/docs/coefficient/fundamentals/accessibility">Accessibility section</Link> for more.\
\
### Coded Component\
\
A component implemented as installable/usable code. When you think of a component library such as Material or Vuetify, these are "coded components".\
\
### Compiled Styles\
\
Combinations of design tokens and other style parameters that have been combined into usable CSS classes, such as a `body-xl` typography class that combines several tokens into a single utility. Compiled styles are all code-generated from our tokens and available as part of our <Link to="/docs/coefficient/framework-support/general-html-css-js">Foundations package</Link>.\
\
### Component\
\
A self-contained piece of UI (e.g., button, card, modal) that encapsulates structure, style, and behavior. It's different from the standard developer-centric definition of a "component", which is what we would call a "coded component".\
\
When we talk about a "component", we mean the abstract definition of a unit of UI as opposed to a specific implementation, e.g. some components may be availalbe as installable "coded components", some may be represented in CSS, some may just exist as documentation.\
\
### Component Library\
  \
A collection of reusable, documented coded components built to implement the design system for a certain platform or tech stack.  \
\
### Design Language\
\
The shared visual and interaction principles that shape a product\'e2\'80\'99s look and feel.  \
\
### Design Token\
\
Design decisions as data. Platform-agnostic variables that store design decisions like color, typography, spacing, and motion (e.g., `color-primary: #0f62fe`). Tokens bridge the gap between how UI is designed in a tool like Figma and implemented in code. \
\
### Documentation Reference Site\
\
Where you are right now. The published home of the design system, where guidelines, code examples, and usage rules are explained. As a user of the design system, this site is your *single source of truth* about Coefficent.\
\
### Guidance\
\
Prescriptive advice for how components and patterns should be used, often including accessibility requirements and do/don\'e2\'80\'99t examples.  \
\
### Pattern\
\
A set of guidance to help solve a class of UI/UX problem that is too application-specific to be a reusable component. For example, form layout and validation are a class of UI problem with broadly-applicable considerations common to most applications but the concrete implementation is very specific to a single application.\
\
### Recipe\
\
A concrete implementation plan for a specific pattern or part of a pattern that is meant to be taken wholesale and used in any application, but which doesn't make sense as a singular component. \
As an example, there may be pattern guidance for forms in general, and then a specific recipe for a "login form" that encapsulates the guidance into an implementation that ensures consistent structure, design, and behavior across any application, but because it would be impossible to design a reusable "login form component" that covers all possible tech stacks and backends, it only exists in recipe form.\
\
### Theming\
\
Theming is the ability to apply different sets of tokens or styles to a system (e.g., light mode, dark mode, brand variations).\
\
In the abstract, a theme is a set of design foundations such as colors, fonts, and component-specific values like elevations, borders, etc, that encapsulates a brand identity or specific look-and-feel.\
\
Concretely, Coefficient aims to provide installable/applyable themes for most of the major platforms we support, such as our <Link to="/docs/coefficient/framework-support/vuetify/">Vuetify theme package</Link>.\
\
### UI Kit\
\
A set of pre-made design assets such as components and patterns (generally implemented in Figma) that designers can use to implement designs and mockups. Some UI kits are specific to a platform or component library, like Sharepoint or SAP, and some are more general to the Coefficient design system. See our <Link to="/docs/coefficient/resources">UI Kits *tk*</Link> page for more.\
\
