## Coefficient Foundations Package\
\
We maintain a package of our "Foundations", which are [design tokens](#what-are-design-tokens) in the form of CSS/SCSS/JS variables and [utility classes](#what-are-compiled-styles) that you can include directly in your project and know that they will always contain the most up-to-date values defined in Coefficient.\
\
## Quickstart\
\
There are two primary ways to use the Coefficient Foundations package based on your needs -- [NPM Package](#npm-package) and [Direct File Include/Git Submodule](#git-submoduledirect-file-include).\
\
### NPM Package\
\
We publish an NPM package called [Coefficient Foundations](https://code.ornl.gov/ords/ornl-design-system/-/tree/main/packages/foundations) that includes exports for each theme's values as well as the top-level tokens and compiled utility classes.\
\
<details>\
<summary>Current Exports</summary>\
\
| Export | Description |\
|--------|-------------|\
| `@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations` | Default JS variables and types export for the ORNL Green theme |\
| `@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green.scss` | SCSS variables for the ORNL Green theme |\
| `@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green.css` | CSS variables with light and dark mode support |\
| `@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green-styles.css` | Utility CSS classes (compiled styles) for typography, spacing, and other styles |\
| `@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green` | JS token exports with theme support |\
\
:::note\
As new color themes get introduced, they will expand these offerings\
:::\
</details>\
\
:::tip\
More specific token documentation for this site is in progress, but until then, please refer to the individual files to see what is available within them. You can find them in your `node_modules/ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/dist` folder.\
:::\
\
#### Installation\
\
This package is hosted in the ORNL on-prem Gitlab instance, and as such you must add the appropriate registry to your `.npmrc` or otherwise let NPM know where to find it.\
\
```shell\
echo @ornl-ux:registry=https://code.ornl.gov/api/v4/projects/17520/packages/npm/ >> .npmrc\
```\
\
:::warning\
\
On some Windows command prompts, using the `echo` command might add unknown invisible unicode characters to your `.npmrc` file and you may get errors trying to install the package, indicating that it can't be found. When in doubt, just make a fresh `.npmrc` file in your project root and copy the contents indicated below.\
\
:::\
\
Alternatively, copy the following into a new or existing `.npmrc` file at your project root:\
\
```shell title=".npmrc"\
@ornl-ux:registry=https://code.ornl.gov/api/v4/projects/17520/packages/npm/\
```\
\
Then you can `npm i @ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations` as normal.\
\
:::info Gitlab Package Registry\
For more information on Gitlab's package registry see the official [Gitlab instructions here](https://code.ornl.gov/help/user/packages/npm_registry/index.md)\
:::\
\
### Git Submodule/Direct File Include\
\
If your project is set up in such a way that you prefer to either include a git submodule or directly download and include specific files, then we also have a separate [Coefficient Compiled Styles](https://code.ornl.gov/ords/ords-compiled-styles) Gitlab repo you can use.\
\
It is effectively a mirror of the Foundations package project (they are both outputs of our codegen process).\
\
Grab anything you need from the `/assets` folder and you're good to go. You will need to manually check for updates or use a git submodule workflow that ensures you have any changes.\
\
:::tip Submodule Includes\
If you only want to include the specific files you need from the submodule and ignore the rest, look into `git sparse-checkout`\
:::\
\
:::warning Experimental Assets\
Anything in the `/assets/experimental` folder are just that - experimental. Use at your own risk\
:::\
\
### Use Coefficient in Your Project\
\
The package supports all the standard ways of including CSS/SCSS/JS in a web project, though your mileage may vary based on project differences.\
\
#### Importing/Referencing\
\
<Tabs>\
<TabItem value="cssimport" label="CSS">\
\
```css\
@import "@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green.css";\
@import "@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green-styles.css"; \
```\
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="cssinjs" label="CSS in JS">\
\
```js\
import "@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green.css"\
import "@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green-styles.css"\
```\
\
:::info CSS Modules\
If you're using CSS Modules in your project, doing an `@import` into a single module isn't a supported use-case, but if you're importing globally you'll be able to access the variables and/or classes from within any downstream modules or components.\
::: \
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="js" label="JavaScript">\
For the JavaScript variables, just import where needed:\
\
```js\
import coefficient from "@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/ornl-green"\
\
const primary_text = coefficient.LIGHT_MODE.primary_text_rich\
```\
\
:::info About JS/TS Variables\
The JS variables are really only intended for if you are going to implement your own high level theming and styling system. In most cases you're going to want to make use of the CSS/SCSS exports to just style your application in which case you don't need the JS variables.\
:::\
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="html" label="HTML">\
\
```html\
<link\
  rel="stylesheet"\
  type="text/css"\
  href="./node_modules/@ornl-ux/coefficient-foundations/dist/ornl-green-vars.css" />\
```\
\
</TabItem>\
</Tabs>\
:::warning Where to Import CSS Token Variables\
These tokens are meant to be global variables, available to your whole application, so the best practice is to import them somewhere at a root level in your application, wherever is appropriate for your framework.\
\
For instance, you could do this in your top level `App.tsx/App.vue` where the main css file is usually imported, or you can import into a top level `app.css`, or you could even pull it in via a `<link>` in the main HTML page header.\
:::\
\
 \
#### Using Coefficient variables in your CSS\
\
The CSS variables work like any other CSS variables, if you've imported them correctly they should be able to be referenced in any of your styles.\
\
Look for opportunities to abstract specific values into a semantic concept, such as a `bg-primary` or `bg-accent` utility class that encapsulates the specific value variable so that if you change themes or change between light and dark mode, everything works without needing changes:\
\
```css \
.bg-primary \{\
  background-color: var(--primary-weak);\
\}\
\
.bg-accent \{\
  background-color: var(--accent-weak);\
\}\
```\
\
For more information on using CSS variables/custom properties, see the [MDN documentation](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_cascading_variables/Using_CSS_custom_properties).\
\
### What are Design Tokens?\
\
Tokens are variables that represent design decisions such as color, typography, and spacing, in a consistent and reusable way.\
\
Essentially they're design values as data.\
\
Tokens allow designers and developers to talk about the implementation of designs using *semantic abstractions*, such as `primary-dark`, instead of *concrete values*, such as `#ab231c`. This creates a separation layer that allows for upstream changes, such as new themes or best practices or brand guidelines, to be implemented with as little change surface area as possible.\
\
For example, if the brand guideline is that primary ORNL green is `#0F8723` and all your main buttons in your application are set to that value and that value changes, you have a lot of changing to do. But if your buttons are set to `var(--ords-primary)` and you get that from this repo, you just have to update the package if that primary color changes.\
\
Tokens are meant to be used as building blocks for bigger things. You can combine them into your own CSS classes or plug them into a customization layer for a component library like Material or use them as the source values for theming a COTS system like Sharepoint.\
\
Tokens are available as SCSS variables, CSS variables, and JS variables (with types).\
\
#### How Do I Use Tokens?\
\
In practice, you'd use these foundational tokens to construct a more comprehensive style, so as an example, if you wanted to construct a global `H1` style that applies all of the appropriate values from the design system, it would look something like:\
\
```css\
h1 \{ \
    font-family: var(--heading-h1-font-family);\
    font-weight: var(--heading-h1-font-weight);\
    font-size: var(--heading-h1-font-size);\
    line-height: var(--heading-h1-line-height);\
    letter-spacing: var(--heading-h1-letter-spacing); \
\}\
```\
\
But, you don't need to create basic foundational utility CSS like this for typography because we also provide compiled styles.\
\
### What are Compiled Styles?\
\
Compiled styles is just a fancy way to say "we turned some of the tokens into usable CSS utility classes."\
\
A good example is a typography class for an `H1` style:\
\
```css\
.ords-heading-h1 \{ \
    font-family: Mulish; \
    font-weight: 500; \
    font-size: 3rem; \
    line-height: 1.2; \
    letter-spacing: -0.02em; \}\
```\
\
This combines the tokens for font family, weight, size, line height, etc, into a single usable class. It doesn't use the variables because it is code-generated from the variables to match to the current theme, but if those variables change in the design system, that class gets re-generated and pushed out with the next version.\
\
:::note What is 'ords'?\
To avoid annoying collisions as much as possible, we namespaced the styles `ords-xxx` which just stands for `Oak Ridge Design System` which seems to be a good enough trade-off of uniqueness/descriptiveness and annoyingness to type because nobody wants to have a bunch of `coefficient-header-h1` in their code.\
:::\
\
The primary use of compiled styles is foundational, global utilities like typography, spacing, elevation, and so on. \
\
The compiled styles will grow over time but will never be a comprehensive representation of all styling in the Coefficient Design System. However, if you find yourself really wishing something were a part of the compiled styles we offer, reach out!\
\
