## Button(Components)\
\
## Implementation\
\
Coefficient is built work with Vuetify's native button compnent `v-btn`. Please refer to Vuetify's documenatation for [v-btn](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/components/buttons) for details on implementation.\
\
## Usage\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--lg margin-bottom--lg">\
	<Column>\
		<Card className="card--full-height padding--md">\
			<CardHeader>\
				<IIcon\
					icon="ph:check-circle-thin"\
					height="48"\
					color="var(--ifm-color-success)"\
				/>\
				When to use\
			</CardHeader>\
			<CardBody>\
				Use buttons to trigger actions in an interface such as submitting a\
				form, saving data, canceling an interaction or opening &amp; closing a\
				modal.\
			</CardBody>\
		</Card>\
	</Column>\
	<Column>\
		<Card className="card--full-height padding--md">\
			<CardHeader>\
				<IIcon\
					icon="ph:x-circle-thin"\
					height="48"\
					color="var(--ifm-color-danger)"\
				/>\
				When not to use\
			</CardHeader>\
			<CardBody>\
				Don't use buttons to navigate users within or between experiences. In\
				those situations please use a\
				[Link](/docs/coefficient/components/link/).\
			</CardBody>\
		</Card>\
	</Column>\
</Columns>\
\
### Label\
\
- Make sure to provide a descriptive, self explaining label that reflects the action that will happen next. Be brief, usually a single verb is best but include a noun if it increases clarity.\
  - Examples:\
  - When a button enables someone to create something new, start with \'e2\'80\'9cNew" and then include the name of the thing they can create (e.g. "New Message")\
  - When a button enables someone to edit an existing set, start with \'e2\'80\'9cEdit" and then include the name of the thing they can edit (e.g. "Edit Contact Info")\
- Use title case and no end punctuation (e.g., "Sign Up" instead of "sign up" or "SIGN UP") to improve readability.\
\
### Style\
\
- Use a primary button for the most important or desired action on a given page.\
- Use demphasized buttons for less important or secondary actions.\
- Use disabled buttons to indicate actions that are currently unavailable or incomplete, and provide context for why the button is disabled.\
\
### Icon\
\
- Add an icon for commonly recognized actions when the icon will improve scannability, such as a check mark for "Confirm" or a trash can for "Delete."\
- Place an icon on the left side of the text when the icon is visually associated with the primary action or draws attention to the button.\
- Place an icon on the right side of the text when the icon represents a secondary aspect of the action or complements it (e.g., an arrow icon to indicate a next step action).\
\
### Grouping\
\
- Buttons can be grouped visually together when there are two or more actions that a user needs to consider in context of each other. A common example is is Save or Cancel\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--lg margin-bottom--lg">\
	<Column>\
		<Card className="card--full-height padding--md">\
			<CardImage cardImageUrl="/img/docs/coefficient/components/button/button-grouping-do.png" />\
			<CardHeader>\
				\
					<IIcon\
						icon="ph:check-circle-thin"\
						height="24"\
						color="var(--ifm-color-success)"\
					/>\{" "\}\
					Do\
				\
			</CardHeader>\
			<CardBody>\
				- Create a logical order with one primary button & a set of lower\
				emphasis buttons\
			</CardBody>\
		</Card>\
	</Column>\
	<Column>\
		<Card className="card--full-height padding--md">\
			<CardImage cardImageUrl="/img/docs/coefficient/components/button/button-grouping-dont.png" />\
			<CardHeader>\
				\
					<IIcon\
						icon="ph:x-circle-thin"\
						height="24"\
						color="var(--ifm-color-danger)"\
					/>\{" "\}\
					Don't\
				\
			</CardHeader>\
			<CardBody>\
				- Place more than one primary action in a group. - Use different levels\
				of secondary emphasis in a group\
			</CardBody>\
		</Card>\
	</Column>\
</Columns>\
\
### Markup\
\
- Using the correct tags for buttons is important because it can disorient users if they hear the wrong tag read out to them by the screen reader.\
- HTML\'c2\'a0`<button>`\'c2\'a0or\'c2\'a0`<input type="button">`:\'c2\'a0Buttons should be created created using the\'c2\'a0`<button>`\'c2\'a0or\'c2\'a0`<input>`\'c2\'a0tag with a\'c2\'a0type="button"\'c2\'a0attribute.\
\
## Accessibility\
\
### Human Impact Overview\
\
- Buttons facilitate user interaction by providing clear, clickable actions on web pages and applications.\
- For users with disabilities, buttons must be easy to identify and use, with alternative methods for interaction, such as keyboard controls.\
- Proper button design helps reduce confusion and ensures that all users can navigate more efficiently.\
\
### WCAG 2.1 A and AA Success Criteria\
\
- [1.4.1](https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#use-of-color) Use of Color: Buttons should not rely solely on color to convey their function. Text labels or universally recognized icons could accompany them.\
- [2.4.7](https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#focus-visible) Focus Visible: Buttons must have a visible focus indicator when navigated to via keyboard.\
- [4.1.2](https://www.w3.org/TR/UNDERSTANDING-WCAG20/ensure-compat-rsv.html) Name, Role, Value: Buttons must have clear names and roles defined to be operable and understandable by user agents, including assistive technologies.\
\
### Keep in mind\
\
- Buttons should display a visible focus state when users tab to them.\
- Screen readers handle buttons and links differently. Pressing the Space/Enter key triggers a button, but pressing the Enter key triggers a link.\
- Provide clear, concise labels for all actions to support users with cognitive disabilities.\
  Avoid using generic labels like \'e2\'80\'9cClick Here\'e2\'80\uc0\u157  for buttons. Use more informative and descriptive labels. Please see our [Guidance](#label) for recommendations.\
\
### Keyboard Interaction\
\
- All buttons must be accessible using the keyboard alone.\
- Buttons can be reached by tab\'c2\'a0and selected with\'c2\'a0space\'c2\'a0or\'c2\'a0enter.\
\
