## Coefficient Vuetify Figma UI Kit\
\
The Coefficient team maintains a Vuetify-specifc UI kit that combines the Vuetify-specific components, variables, and settings with Coefficient's design tokens, allowing designers and developers to work directly with Vuetify components and properties without the friction of an additional translation step to convert designs to their Vuetify equivalents.\
\
Not only does this reduce the communication gap between developers and designers, it also ensures designers are working within the realm of what already exists, increasing the overall efficency of everyone involved.\
\
Get the [UI Kit here](https://www.figma.com/design/mjyvXN2dNQ71t7nNwMJTaL/Vuetify-UI-Kit?m=auto)!\
\
## Coefficient Vuetify Theme Package\
\
[project README](https://code.ornl.gov/ords/ornl-design-system/-/blob/main/packages/vuetify-theme/README.md)\
\
### Quickstart\
\
To get up and running with the theme package in your project, you'll need to install it and wire it up to your Vuetify config.\
\
#### Installation\
\
This package is hosted in the ORNL on-prem Gitlab instance, and as such you must add the appropriate registry to your `.npmrc` or otherwise let NPM know where to find it.\
\
```shell title="command line"\
echo @ornl-ux:registry=https://code.ornl.gov/api/v4/projects/17520/packages/npm/ >> .npmrc\
```\
\
:::warning\
\
On some Windows command prompts, using the `echo` command might add unknown invisible unicode characters to your `.npmrc` file and you may get errors trying to install the package, indicating that it can't be found. When in doubt, just make a fresh `.npmrc` file in your project root and copy the contents indicated below.\
\
:::\
\
Alternatively, copy the following into a new or existing `.npmrc` file at your project root:\
\
```shell title=".npmrc"\
@ornl-ux:registry=https://code.ornl.gov/api/v4/projects/17520/packages/npm/\
```\
\
Once you've pointed NPM at the `@ornl-ux` registry source,  you can install as normal.\
\
```shell npm2yarn\
npm i @ornl-ux/coefficient-vuetify-theme\
```\
\
The package also has a peer dependency on [@phosphor-icons/vue](https://github.com/phosphor-icons/vue), so if you intend to use the icon set (optional), you need that as well.\
\
(from partial)\
\
#### Setup and Use\
\
To wire up the Vuetify theme and use it in your project, you need to:\
\
- [ ] Import the theme\
- [ ] Set Up the SCSS Variables\
- [ ] Install Mulish Font\
- [ ] Install Icons\
\
:::info Vuetify Themes\
For more information about using custom themes in Vuetify, see the [official documentation](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/features/theme/#custom-themes).\
:::\
\
<Tabs>\
\
<TabItem value="import" label="Import Theme">\
\
##### Import Theme\
\
Import themes into your Vuetify loader and update your `createVuetify(...)` call to use them:\
\
```javascript\
import "vuetify/styles"\
\
// Composables\
import \{ createVuetify \} from "vuetify"\
import \{ ORDS, ORDSDark \} from "@ornl-ux/coefficient-vuetify-theme"\
\
// https://vuetifyjs.com/en/introduction/why-vuetify/#feature-guides\
export default createVuetify(\{\
	theme: \{\
		defaultTheme: "ORDS",\
		themes: \{\
			ORDS,\
			ORDSDark,\
		\},\
	\},\
\})\
```\
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="sass" label="SCSS Variables">\
\
Use the `_ords.scss` variables in your SASS entrypoint (probably `settings.scss`) and override the appropriate Vuetify settings\
\
```scss\
@use "@ornl-ux/coefficient-vuetify-theme/_ords.scss" as ords;\
\
@forward "vuetify/settings" with (\
	$body-font-family: ords.$body-font-family,\
	$border-radius-root: ords.$border-radius-root,\
	$font-weights: ords.$font-weights,\
	$typography: ords.$typography\
);\
```\
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="font" label="Font">\
\
Import the [`Mulish`](https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Mulish?query=mulish) font into your application. If you're using Vite you can use a font-loader in your `vite.config.ts` (this is technically optional but Mulish is the official brand font for the ORNL theme).\
\
```javascript\
ViteFonts(\{\
    google: \{\
      families: [\
        \{\
          name: "Mulish",\
          styles: "ital,wght@0,200..1000;1,200..1000",\
        \},\
      ],\
    \},\
  \}),\
```\
\
</TabItem>\
<TabItem value="icons" label="Icons">\
\
Add the [Phosphor Icons](https://phosphoricons.com/) to your application (This is technically optional but the Phosphor Icons are the official ORNL brand iconset).\
\
1. Install the [Phosphor Icons Vue package](https://github.com/phosphor-icons/vue#installation) if you haven't already (see [installation](#installation)).\
\
2. Next, add the iconset into your Vue application:\
\
```javascript\
// index.ts or similar ...\
import \{ ORDSIconSet \} from "@ornl-ux/coefficient-vuetify-theme"\
\
app.use(ORDSIconSet).use(vuetify).use(router)\
```\
\
1. Next, in your Vuetify loader, import the `aliases` and `phosphor` objects and add an `icons` key to your `createVuetify()` call:\
\
```javascript\
import "@mdi/font/css/materialdesignicons.css"\
import "vuetify/styles"\
import \{ aliases, ORDS, ORDSDark, phosphor \} from "@ornl-ux/coefficient-vuetify-theme"\
//...\
export default createVuetify(\{\
	icons: \{\
		defaultSet: "mdi",\
		aliases: \{\
			...aliases,\
		\},\
		sets: \{ phosphor \},\
	\},\
	theme: \{\
		defaultTheme: "ORDS",\
  ...\
  \}\
\})\
```\
\
:::tip\
if you leave the `defaultSet` as `"mdi"` you can also still use the material icons that come packaged with Vuetify by default, e.g. `<v-icon icon="mdi-pencil-outline"></v-icon>`.\
:::\
\
##### Using Additional Phosphor Icons\
\
The `ORDSIconSet` loader is optimized to only register the components defined by the iconset, which is a small subset of the overall Phosphor package. To use others, you'll need to also load them in here individually, e.g.:\
\
```javascript\
//...\
import \{ PhArmchair \} from "@phosphor-icons/vue"\
\
app.component("PhArmchair", PhArmchair)\
```\
\
And then you can use a `<PhArmchair />` component anywhere in your app.\
\
:::info\
You can also just [globally install the full Phosphor iconset](https://github.com/phosphor-icons/vue#global-install) in your app (in which case you don't need the `ORDSIconSet` loader) though this is generally not recommended by the maintainers as it may not play well with tree shaking. But if convienience outweighs bundle size, go for it.\
:::\
\
