## Accessibility\
\
\
Accessibility (A11y) is a fundamental part of user experience (UX). It is through accessibility that we ensure that everyone can use applications and websites developed by Oak Ridge National Laboratory effectively and efficiently.\
\
While accessibility is critical to ensure equitable access to digital applications for people with one or more disabilities that may affect how they move, see, hear, communicate, learn, understand, and process information, a focus on accessibility is, at root, a focus on ensuring that *everyone* has the best possible user experience.\
\
At ORNL, accessibility matters for three big reasons: \
\
1. It\'e2\'80\'99s the right thing to do - Inclusion strengthens our science, our collaborations, and our community. \
\
2. It\'e2\'80\'99s the law - We must meet requirements such as Section 508 and WCAG 2.1 AA. Our global collaborations often require meeting other international accessibility laws, too. \
\
3. It\'e2\'80\'99s good for innovation and reach - Accessibility improves usability for everyone, makes content easier to find and share, and ensures our work reaches the widest possible audience. \
\
## Accessibility Playbook\
\
For a deep dive into all things Accessibility, check out our [Accessibility Playbook *link tk*](../)\
\
## Component and Pattern Accessibility\
\
Accessibility guidance is available for each component and pattern implemented in the system. Check the pages dedicated to whichever component you're interested in to learn more.\
\
## Regulatory Requirements\
\
Accessibility is a regulatory requirement under [Section 508](https://section508.gov).\
\
Section 508 is the sub-section of the U.S. Rehabilitation Act of 1973 that requires electronic content produced by the federal government be accessible to people with disabilities. It also sets the accessibility standards for websites, applications, digital kiosks and other digital communications tools and content, known as information communication technology (ICT). The goal of Section 508 is to ensure that people with disabilities have equal access to government information and services through its digital content.\
\
Under Section 508 there are four primary principles of accessibility:\
\
- **Perceivable**: Users must be able to perceive the information presented.\
- **Operable**: Users must be able to operate the interface.\
- **Understandable**: Users must be able to understand both how the user interface operates and the meaning of information presented.\
- **Robust**: Users must be able to access the content as technologies advance. As technologies like browsers and other assistive technology evolve, the content should remain accessible.\
\
## We Test for Accessibility, You Should Too\
\
While we have rigorously tested and validated Coefficient against the most stringent accessibility rules possible, that's only the first step to ensuring accessible applications.\
\
At both the design phase and the implementation phase, it's critical to test your own application for accessibility. You can reference our [component](../components/) documentation, our [patterns & recipes](../patterns/), and our [Accessibility Playbook](../) for guidance.\
\
