## Color\
\
\
The semantics, patterns, and abstractions that define Coefficient's color system.\
\
## How we think about color\
\
### Color has explicit meaning and purpose\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--lg">\
  <Column className="padding-left--none col col--8">\
\
Color is an essential element in web applications, influencing user perception and interaction. Each color carries its own set of meanings and emotions, which can significantly impact how users engage with the interface. For example, red is often associated with urgency or danger, making it an effective choice for alerts or warnings. By thoughtfully incorporating these colors into the design, developers can create a more intuitive user experience. A well-planned color scheme not only enhances the aesthetic appeal of the application but also serves as a navigational tool, guiding users toward their goals. When users can easily interpret the visual cues provided by color, they are more likely to interact confidently and efficiently with the application, ultimately leading to a more satisfying experience.\
\
  </Column>\
  <Column className="padding-right--none col col--4">\
    \
  </Column>\
</Columns>\
\
### Color acts as an affordance for action\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--md">\
  <Column className="padding-left--none col col--8">\
\
Color serves as a powerful affordance in web applications, guiding users toward actionable elements. By utilizing distinct colors for buttons, links, and interactive features, designers can create visual cues that indicate where users should focus their attention. For instance, vibrant hues like blue or green can signal clickable items, while muted tones may suggest non-interactive content. This intentional use of color not only enhances usability but also fosters a more engaging experience, as users can quickly identify pathways for interaction and navigate the interface with confidence.\
\
  </Column>\
  <Column className="padding-right--none col col--4">\
    \
  </Column>\
</Columns>\
\
### Color creates hierarchy\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--md">\
  <Column className="padding-left--none col col--8">\
\
Color is important for establishing visual hierarchy within web applications. By strategically using different colors, designers can guide users' attention to the most important elements on a page. For instance, a vibrant color can highlight primary actions, while softer hues can be used for secondary information, creating a clear distinction between various levels of content. This intentional use of color not only enhances the aesthetic appeal but also improves usability, allowing users to navigate the interface more intuitively. When users can easily discern the importance of elements through color differentiation, they are more likely to engage effectively with the application.\
\
  </Column>\
  <Column className="padding-right--none col col--4">\
    \
  </Column>\
</Columns>\
\
### Color powers accessible experiences\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--md">\
  <Column className="padding-left--none col col--8">\
\
Color plays a critical role in creating accessible web applications, enhancing both usability and aesthetic appeal. By ensuring that color contrast adheres to established accessibility standards, designers can significantly improve navigation for all users, including those with visual impairments. Thoughtful color selections not only help differentiate between various interface elements but also create a more engaging experience. This inclusivity fosters confidence among users, allowing them to interact with the application without hesitation, ultimately leading to a more satisfying user journey.\
\
  </Column>\
  <Column className="padding-right--none col col--4">\
    \
  </Column>\
</Columns>\
\
## Semantic System Colors\
\
System colors are named to reflect their purpose within the system. We provide (and can work with you to create) themes with color ramps defined for each system color.  In the table below we are representing an `ORNL Green` theme which is derived from our color system and defined in collaboration between UX and Creative services to reflect the ORNL brand.\
\
| Role | Description |\
| -- | -- | \
| Primary | Primary is the primary color of the system and is used to denote the interactivity of an element and is associated with the most important actions of an interaction point. |\
| Supporting | Supporting is used to highlight actions that are important, but don\'e2\'80\'99t directly help the user achieve the goal of a page. Secondary should be reserved for elements or information that complement the primary focus that draws attention to an action without disrupting the flow. |\
| Accent | Accent should be used sparingly throughout the design of a page. It can be used for elements that need to stand out and call attention to themselves and also for visual pops of color that maintain cohesion with the brand. |\
| Neutral | Neutral should be used to de-emphasize interactions that are less important or not encouraged. It is also for non-interactive elements, backgrounds, borders, and typography to provide a consistent and balanced visual experience. |\
| Danger | Danger is used to communicate errors or critical issues that require immediate attention or indicate potential negative consequences. |\
| Warning | Warning is used to indicate potential hazards, risks, or situations that require caution before proceeding with an action. |\
| Success | Success is used to communicate positive outcomes, confirmations, or the successful completion of a task. |\
| Information | Info is used to indicate that there is important information that the user should be aware of that isn\'e2\'80\'99t necessarily system critical. |\
\
## Color Applications\
\
Semantic system tokens are also provided help color to be implemented consistently, accessibly, and purposefully across ORNL's experiences.  Here are some of the common applications of color (and recommendations for how tokens could be leveraged for each) that you'll come across when building expereinces at ORNL.\
\
### Surfaces & Backgrounds\
\
Surfaces are the backbone of most designs. They are a way to convey hierarchy and separation among background elements and containers without the use of a border or divider.\
\
We recommend using neutrals as the foundation for most backgrounds (`--neutral-bg-*`, `--surface-*`).\
\
Please reserve color backgrounds for use cases where emphasis is needed (like in Heroes, Cards or Calls to action).  For example: notification panels (--info-bg-soft), confirmation states (--success-bg-soft), or warnings (--warning-bg-soft).\
\
Please try to avoid overusing vivid colors behind large amounts of body content as depending on the implementation it can reduce readability and accessibility.\
\
### Text\
\
For overall body text we recommend relying on neutral tokens (and using these will naturally handle both light and dark implementations):\
\
- `--neutral-text-strong` for primary copy.\
- `--neutral-text-emphasis` for secondary text or metadata.\
\
We also recommend using semantic colors to convey meaning for specific use cases:\
\
- `--success-text-*` for positive outcomes.\
- `--danger-text-*` for errors or destructive actions.\
- `--warning-text-*` for cautions or alerts.\
- `--info-text-*` for informational highlights.\
\
For accent or primary text colors (e.g., --primary-text-emphasis) we recommend using those sparingly\'e2\'80\'94to highlight key text, selected states, or interactive text.\
\
### Icons\
\
Icon colors should follow a similar pattern as text colors to ensure that icons can be used with text content consistently\
\
For base icons we recommend using neutral colors such as `--icon-medium` or `--neutral-icon-strong` to maintain contrast with text.\
\
For status icons we recommend leveraging the semantic colors directly (e.g. `--success-icon-strong` for positive outcomes, `--warning-icon-strong` for cautions or alerts, etc...)\
\
### Borders\
\
Borders provide separation between elements in a design. They can be applied as a part of a component or independently in the form of dividers.\
\
For default borders: use neutral tones like `--neutral-border-subtle` or `--border-light`.\
\
For interactive elements: try to align the border color with intent. e.g. `--primary-border-strong` for active states, `--danger-border-emphasis` for error states.\
\
For dividers: use subtle contrasts (`--neutral-border-soft` or opacity variants) to define sections without drawing attention.\
\
## Accessibility Considerations\
\
- Always verify contrast ratios between background and text (\'e2\'89\'a5 4.5:1 for body, \'e2\'89\'a5 3:1 for large text).\
- Focus on semantic meaning first.  Hue\'e2\'80\'94color alone should never convey critical information.\
- Ensure dark theme parity, using provided inverted semantic variables to maintain brand consistency in all modes.\
\
## Frequently Asked Questions\
\
### How do I pick which color to use?\
\
Picking the right color for your component can be difficult, but we can help you find the right solution by answering a simple question:\
\
How important is this action to the user?\
\
Think about the context of your page. What is the user trying to accomplish, and does this element help them achieve that goal? \
For example, if the user is trying submit a form, the button that the user clicks to submit the form is almost certainly a primary action. However, if the user is trying to submit a form and the button is a link that will take them to a different page or otherwise distract from the primary action, it\'e2\'80\'99s likely a secondary action.\
\
### What if I have multiple important actions on a page?\
\
They can all be primary! The system has multiple ways of showing hierarchy and visual weight in a design. If you have multiple actions that feel important, they can all be primary.\
\
### What if I don\'e2\'80\'99t have any secondary actions?\
\
That\'e2\'80\'99s okay! Color is only one way of showing the hierarchy in a design. Not every page will have secondary actions, it\'e2\'80\'99s just a way to provide affordances to a user when an action is important, but not serving their immediate goal.\
\
### How do I know how much of each color to use?\
\
Using the components provided in the Coefficient UI Kit should provide you with a well balanced design. However, if your design feels off and seems like it could use some tweaking, try following the 60-30-10 rule of design:\
\
- 60% of the colored elements in a design should use the primary color\
- 30% of the colored elements in a design should use the secondary color\
- 10% of the colored elements in a design should use the accent color\
- Use neutrals liberally to balance the design\
\
Note that these ratios are not hard rules, but a guideline that can be helpful when you\'e2\'80\'99re struggling to create something that works visually.\
