## Type ramp\
\
Our type ramp is built to support most typography use cases needed at the lab. \
\
If you are able to leverage our tokens directly that is the recommended approach as the tokens bring along all their settings automatically.  However if you are not able to leverage our tokens then we also provide the specs for each level of the ramp as well. Details on both can be found in our [General HTML/CSS/JS](/docs/coefficient/framework-support/general-html-css-js) documentation.\
\
While using these styles, please keep in mind the hierarchy and the intended use cases for each style.\
\
### Display \
\
Use to introduce key moments in the UI. Display creates high visibility and should be used sparingly. Its ideal for hero banners, landing pages and marketing sections.\
\
#### Display properties\
\
- Extra-bold weights (900) for strong visual presence\
- Very large sizes (3rem \'e2\'80\'93 7.5rem)\
- Tighter letter spacing to feel clean and modern\
- Single-line emphasis (line-height: 1)\
\
#### Display is good for\
\
- Page hero titles\
- Dashboard \'e2\'80\'9cbig number\'e2\'80\uc0\u157  visualizations\
- Section intros and marketing panels\
\
### Header\
\
Use to introduce content sections and define visual hierarchy. Headers create order and support scannability.\
\
#### Header properties\
\
- Medium font weight (500) for clarity and structure\
- Consistent line-height of 1.2 for readable multi-line titles\
- Logical step-downs in size from 3rem to 1rem\
\
#### Header is good for\
\
- Page titles (H1)\
- Section headings (H2\'e2\'80\'93H3)\
- Inline group labels and card titles (H4\'e2\'80\'93H6)\
\
Please follow semantic HTML structure as much as possible (H1, then H2, etc.). This helps accessibility, screen readers, and document scanning. Screen readers for example use headings to help users navigate quickly through content and correct structure improves understanding and accessibility.\
\
**The specific accessibility standard we follow:**\
WCAG 2.1, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels (Level AA) ([Reference](https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/headings-and-labels.html))\
\
- Use proper semantic HTML elements (``, ``, ``, etc.) to establish a clear information hierarchy.\
- Headings should be meaningful and descriptive, not just styled visually.\
- Maintain logical heading order (don\'e2\'80\'99t jump from `` to ``, for example).\
\
:::tip When to use Display vs Header\
\
Display is intended to be used for visual impact and attention-grabbing use cases whereas Heading is intended to aid readability and create hierarchy within the structure of a user experience.\
\
  \
    \
      Use Display\
      \
        For large, prominent text elements such as heros, banners, and featured text\
        When creating visual interest is the priority\
        For brand statements or key messages\
      \
    \
  \
  \
    \
      Use Heading\
      \
        For section titles, subheadings, and content organization\
        For creating a clear information hierarchy in a document\
        Please see the \'e2\'80\'9cSemantic Hierarchy\'e2\'80\uc0\u157  section below for best practices on structure\
      \
    \
