## Forms\
\
Forms enable our users to enter information and complete tasks across ORNL experiences. This guidance combines input, select, and button components with other context-specific guidance to create usable and accessible forms that help users enter accurate information with clear instructions.\
\
## Anatomy\
\
<Columns className="margin-top--lg margin-bottom--lg">\
	<Column>\
		<Card className="card--full-height padding--md">\
			<CardImage cardImageUrl="/img/docs/coefficient/patterns/forms-anatomy.png" />\
		</Card>\
	</Column>\
</Columns>\
\
1. **Field labels:** Text indicating the purpose of each field and whether information is required.\
2. **Message text:** Optional additional guidance about format requirements or field purpose.\
3. **States:** Implement states to help inform a user of their status in a given form.\
4. **Actions:** Buttons enabling users to submit, cancel or conduct other form actions.\
\
## Usage\
\
- **Keep it focused:** Focus on collecting only information needed for the core task &amp; remove fields that can be derived elsewhere or collected more conveniently later. See the [Content > Fields](#fields) section below for more information.\
- **Be logical:** Order fields from the user's perspective, not the system's perspective. Design the form as a conversation between you and the user. See the [Layout](#layout) section below for more information.\
- **Make it accessible:** Ensure that users can interact with the form from any mode (e.g. keyboard, screen reader, etc...) or device (desktop, mobile, etc...)\
- **Provide clarity:** Use clear language for labels and message text that guide the user to what information should be entered in each field. See the [Content > Labels](#labels) section below for more information.\
\
### Overview\
\
#### Components\
\
- Match the input component used to content and action you want the user to take.\
- Use native HTML controls as they provide the ability to trigger appropriate mobile keyboards, zooming options and can provide built-in validation\
- Size fields appropriately (narrow for postal codes, wider for addresses) to provides visual cues about expected input length and type of content that is expected.\
- Use HTML autocomplete attributes to help browsers and password managers auto-fill forms, this will help reduce completion time for returning users on commonly used forms.\
\
