\
#### Calls to action\
\
- **Make primary actions prominent:** The main action should be visually distinct through color, size, or positioning. Use "primary" styling for the main action button.\
- **Position primary actions consistently:** Place the primary action in the same location across forms to build user expectations and reduce cognitive load.\
- **Provide clear secondary actions:** Include secondary actions like "Cancel" or "Save Draft" when appropriate, but make them visually less prominent than the primary action.\
- **Enable keyboard navigation:** Ensure all form actions can be triggered using keyboard navigation (Tab, Enter, Space) to support accessibility.\
\
#### Validation & feedback\
\
- **Provide immediate validation feedback:** Show validation messages as users complete fields (on blur) rather than waiting for form submission. This allows users to correct errors while context is fresh.\
- **Use inline error messages:** Display error messages directly next to relevant input fields rather than at the top of the form. This creates a clear connection between the error and its location.\
- **Show progress indicators:** For multi-step forms, show users their current position and remaining steps. This helps manage expectations and reduces abandonment.\
- **Preserve user input during errors:** When validation fails, preserve all correct user input so users don't have to re-enter information.\
\
#### Optional vs. required fields\
\
- Always ensure required fields are clearly labeled as it will help users scan for necessary information and reduces errors.\
- Add `(*)` to indicate if a field is required\
  - Adding `(*)` alongside the label ensures it\'e2\'80\'99s easy to associate with the field its for, particularly when instructions at the top might not be visible while scrolling.\
  - Include a space between the last word of the label and the first parenthesis.\
- **When required is implied**\
  - Understanding its recommended to label required fields, there are cases where it\'e2\'80\'99s implied that the field is required. This is common when there\'e2\'80\'99s a one or two fields fundamental to completing of a task, like the username and password fields on a login screen.\
  - In these cases, marking the fields required isn\'e2\'80\'99t necessary but can add additional clarity.\
- **Labeling optional fields**\
  - It\'e2\'80\'99s not generally necessary to mark which fields are optional. While doing so can support clarity, it also adds unnecessary visual noise.\
  - We recommend to only denote required fields however if you choose also denote option fields then please apply that choice consistently to avoid confusion.\
\
### Layout\
\
#### Order fields logically\
\
- Display fields in an order that is logical from the user's perspective; not to your backend.\
- Think of the form as a conversation with the user; what should you know before asking for the next piece of information?\
\
#### Group related information\
\
- Use descriptive headings to organize related fields into logical sections. This helps users understand the form's structure and track their progress.\
- For longer forms, consider breaking them into steps to prevent users from feeling overwhelmed.\
\
#### Position labels above input fields\
\
- Top-aligned labels are easier to scan and work better across different screen sizes, creating a clear visual connection between label and input.\
- Note: For frameworks leveraging Material as their root (like Vuetify), please continue to follow Material's out of the box structure for labels (e.g. where the label starts visually inside the input and then moves above the input field when focused). For more details see: [Vuetify](/docs/coefficient/framework-support/vuetify/)\
\
### Content\
\
#### Fields\
\
Only include fields needed for the core task. Remove fields which collect information that can be (a) derived in some other way or (b) collected more conveniently later.\
\
