The following questions can help you work through the purpose of each field in a given form to make sure you're collecting the right data while also keeping the form accessible for your users.\
\
1. What question are we asking of the user? (the exact field/input)\
2. Who in our organization uses this data? (specific person/role, not just department)\
3. What exactly do they use it for? (specific business process or decision)\
4. Based on the above; is this answer required or optional?\
5. What would happen if someone entered fake/incomplete data just to proceed?\
6. Could we prepopulate this field from existing data?\
7. Could we estimate this value using system data (user context, previous entries, defaults)?\
8. Can we simplify data entry for this field (dropdowns, auto-complete, smart defaults)?\
9. What's the cost to the user if we don't collect this data?\
10. What's the user friction of collecting this data?\
\
#### Labels\
\
- **Use clear, descriptive labels:** Labels should clearly describe what information is needed without jargon or ambiguous terms. Users should understand what to enter without additional explanation.\
- **Use sentence case for labels:** Sentence case (capitalizing only the first word) is easier to read and maintains consistency with other interface text.\
- **Don't use placeholder text as labels:** Placeholder text disappears when users start typing, making it difficult to review entries and causing accessibility issues. Use helper text for format examples instead.\
\
#### Buttons\
\
- Please see [Button](/docs/coefficient/components/button#label) for guidance on creating button labels\
\
#### Message text\
\
- Show users the expected format for complex inputs through helper text. This is especially important when format requirements aren't obvious (e.g., whether decimals are allowed).\
\
#### Errors\
\
- Error messages should explain what went wrong and how to fix it using plain language. Avoid technical jargon or system-generated error codes.\
\
