## Accessibility\
\
### Semantic Structure and Landmarks\
\
Use semantic HTML to clearly define page regions.\
\
- Wrap the header in a native `<header>` element.\
- Use `<nav>` for navigation regions.\
- Apply `role="search"` to search components when applicable.\
\
Landmarks should be used intentionally. Overuse can create noise for screen reader users and make the page structure harder to understand.\
\
### Navigation Organization and Hierarchy\
\
- Avoid placing commonly used menu items last, since keyboard users must navigate sequentially.\
- Use list elements for navigation links to improve screen reader comprehension.\
\
### Keyboard Navigation\
\
- Users must be able to tab through all interactive elements.\
- Top level navigation items must receive visible focus.\
- Use Enter or Space to activate links and open dropdowns.\
- Dropdown menus must open via click or keyboard interaction, not hover, since they are difficult for users with motor or vision impairments and do not work on touch devices.\
\
### Skip Navigation Links\
\
Provide a skip navigation link to allow users to bypass the long navigation lists and jump directly to main content.\
\
- Add a skip navigation link before the header and place it at the very top of the page.\
- The link should be visible on focus.\
- The link must point to an id at the beginning of the main content area.\
- Avoid placing other interactive elements before the skip link.\
\
Read more: [Skip Navigation Links from WebAIM](https://webaim.org/techniques/skipnav/)\
\
### Icons and Visual Elements\
\
- Always pair icons with visible text labels.\
- Do not replace navigation labels with icons.\
\
### Logo Accessibility\
\
- Provide alternative text for logo images.\
- If the logo is text, use a neutral inline element such as ``.\
- Do not use an h1 for the logo unless it is the homepage.\
\
## Framework Notes\
\
While the "Slot" concept is framework-agnostic, specific implementations may require adapting native components to match this guidance.\
\
<Tabs>\
	<TabItem value="header-vueitfy" label="Vueitfy">\
		import CodeBlock from "@theme/CodeBlock"\
import VuetifyHeaderSource from "!!raw-loader!../../../shared/vuetify/code/headerTemplate.vue"\
\
Teams using Vuetify can directly leverage its [v-app-bar](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/components/app-bars) or [v-toolbar](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/components/toolbars) components. The slot architecture maps well to Vuetify's layout logic by utilizing the v-spacer component to control alignment.\
\
- **Branding Slot:** Use the `v-app-bar-title` or `v-toolbar-title` component (depending on which root component you selected). This ensures the logo or site title remains anchored to the left.\
- **Navigation Slot:** Place top-level navigation items immediately after the branding title. Note: For mobile layouts, use v-app-bar-nav-icon to house collapsed navigation which will help implement the [Responsive Behavior](#responsive-behavior) guidance from above.\
- **The Split (Spacer):** Insert a `<v-spacer></v-spacer>` component after the navigation items. This can be used to push everything following it to the align to the right, creating the separation between Navigation and User Actions.\
- **User Actions Slot:** Place icon buttons or toggles after the spacer to anchor them to the right.\
\
